TopicTitle: [1.6.X] Surface Experiment Pack - Deployable science for KIS/KAS! (v2.7 - 13/Jan/19)

Articles.Content: Is CKAN installation valid or it's prefered to manual download and use KSP AVC?

@Antik CKAN should be fine. It requires KIS, and KAS, which CKAN will handle. There may be some problems if you try to install both the old and the new version of KAS (CKAN should only install the old version by default); those are two separate things that might not play together well with this mod.

Also, are lockers and box supposed to be that, no, THAT spacious? If yes, why?

Edit: nevermind, should just used standart KIS SC-62 container for compaison.

Edited February 14, 2017 by Antik

uhhhhhhhhhh why won't my station auto transmit (yes I have the appropriate node unlocked in the tech tree).

Could it have something to do with RemoteTech?

 

pic:

45 minutes ago, JayPee said:

uhhhhhhhhhh why won't my station auto transmit (yes I have the appropriate node unlocked in the tech tree).

Could it have something to do with RemoteTech?

 

I've had to attach a antenna to the SEP station to get a connection using Remote Tech.  I know CobaltWolf said its RT friendly but I can never get a connection without installing an antenna on it.
@CarnageINC okay i'll try that, thanks
doesn't seem to have worked
@JayPee Did you turn on auto-transmit for that station?

@DMagic @JayPee I've found similar behavior with RemoteTech and SEP. For instance, I have a small SEP base near the runway. The wireless symbol is lit green, but there are no bars, despite the KSC being a couple of thousand meters away. I tried a previous poster's suggestion and placed an omnidirectional antenna on the SEP central station to no effect.

@DMagic yes.  BTW thanks for all your continued work, i use and enjoy several of your mods.

@doktorstick I'm having the same behavior - green icon lit, no bars.  the SEP station pictured above is about 1.3 km SW of the West end of my runway.

The connection strength indicator only applies to stock CommNet, not anything else. It only affects the rate of data collection, not data transmission.

It should be able to transmit data fine when using RT, but it's possible that something has changed, or something hasn't been taken into account when checking for the viability of transmission. Auto-transmission requires enough EC onboard to actually complete the transmission, regardless of whether the station is loaded or not; there could be a problem with that calculation when RT is used.

Is there anything in the log files about an SEP transmission failing?

@DMagic I'll check tonight when I get home.  This post will be edited to contain my report to you.

Update: No, I searched KSP.log for 'SEP transmission' and 'SEP fail' with no results.  Here's a copy in case you're a masochist.
